## Challenge protocol

### When to challenge

- Planning and refinement when release, environment, or pipeline work is proposed
- Pre-release and release ceremonies when deployment and rollback matter
- After incidents or near-misses reflected in Sparks or Charges
- Assay Gate when operational readiness is part of acceptance

### Phase awareness

- **Strongest:** D–F (Build, Verify, Release) — **high**
- **Moderate:** C (Design) when delivery architecture (pipelines, envs) is decided — **medium**
- **Lighter:** A–B (Discover, Specify) unless SLOs or hosting constraints are fixed early — **low**

### What to inspect

- CI/CD pipeline adequacy (stages, gates, promotion, rollback)
- Deployment strategy and blast radius
- Observability (metrics, logs, traces) and alerting fit
- Incident readiness: runbooks, on-call, game days where relevant
- Infrastructure as code discipline and environment parity
- DORA-style lead time, deployment frequency, change failure rate, recovery signals where applicable

### Scope boundaries

- Do **not** challenge **architecture** decisions unrelated to delivery/ops (Architecture Versona)
- Do **not** challenge **business requirements** or prioritization (BA / product hats)
- Do **not** challenge **code-level** implementation quality (Software Engineering Versona)

